description: Amid a deepening crisis barely a year after Labour's return to power, the popular deputy prime minister, Angela Rayner, was forced to resign. David Lammy, the foreign secretary, has replaced her, with Yvette Cooper taking over his role.

description: The US's reinforced interventionism in business signals the emergence of 'post-neoliberal' capitalism, observes Le Monde's Marie Charrel in her column. This marks the state's return in the service of an authoritarian project that disregards redistribution and social justice.

headline: Indie favorite Jarmusch beats Gaza war film for Venice top prize
description: 'Father Mother Sister Brother' is the first Jim Jarmusch film to compete at Venice. Jarmusch signaled his opposition to Israel's continued siege and bombardment of Gaza by wearing a badge saying 'Enough' at the Venice awards ceremony.

headline: Demna's thread between streetwear and haute couture
description: 'Essence of a Style' (5/6). Appointed to the helm of some of the biggest fashion houses, six designers are set to command the industry's attention this season. We look back at what has defined their distinctive touch so far, before their trial by fire. In this chapter, the former artistic director of Balenciaga, who is now at Gucci.

headline: Isabelle Adjani, the masterfully ambiguous Queen Margot
description: 'Adjani, The Famous Stranger' (5/6). After four years of hesitation that gave the director Patrice Chéreau many sleepless nights, the actress finally agreed to act in this bloody adaptation of an Alexandre Dumas novel.

description: Jean Pormanove, a 46-year-old streamer, died on August 18 while streaming live on the Kick platform. He launched his career by streaming the video game 'Fortnite,' but ultimately became the star of a humiliating spectacle.

headline: 'Block Everything': Anger in France is deep, but mass strikes appear unlikely
description: The choice of a Wednesday for the planned September 10 protests raises questions about who has the option to strike, especially as labor disputes in French workplaces have been particularly rare in recent years.

headline: 'Dear Salman Rushdie…': Isabelle Adjani's stand against religious fundamentalism
description: 'Adjani, The Famous Stranger' (4/6). After Iran issued a fatwa against the British writer in 1989, the French actress used the César Awards ceremony to show her support for the author of 'The Satanic Verses.' She was one of the few in the film industry to take such a stand.
